{
  "class_purpose": "AbstractResponse is the common base class for all Kafka response messages. It provides shared functionality such as serialization, deserialization, error counting utilities, throttle‑time handling, and API‑key identification, while delegating the concrete response payload handling to subclasses.",
  "key_fields": [
    {
      "name": "DEFAULT_THROTTLE_TIME",
      "description": "Constant representing the default (zero) throttle time in milliseconds when a response schema does not include a throttle field."
    },
    {
      "name": "apiKey",
      "description": "The ApiKeys value that identifies which Kafka API this response belongs to. It is set in the constructor and used for parsing and for exposing the API type via the apiKey() method."
    }
  ],
  "key_methods": [
    {
      "name": "AbstractResponse(ApiKeys apiKey)",
      "description": "Protected constructor that records the API key for the concrete response subclass."
    },
    {
      "name": "toSend(ResponseHeader header, short version)",
      "description": "Creates a Send object that contains the full response (header + body) with a size prefix, ready to be written to the network."
    },
    {
      "name": "serializeWithHeader(ResponseHeader header, short version)",
      "description": "Serializes the response together with its header into a ByteBuffer, but **without** the leading size prefix (used internally by toSend)."
    },
    {
      "name": "serialize(short version)",
      "description": "Serializes only the response body (the protocol message) into a ByteBuffer. Primarily used in tests."
    },
    {
      "name": "errorCounts()",
      "description": "Abstract method that concrete responses must implement to return a map of Errors → occurrence count for the whole response."
    },
    {
      "name": "errorCounts(Errors error)",
      "description": "Utility that creates a singleton map for a single error (used by subclasses that have only one error field)."
    },
    {
      "name": "errorCounts(Stream<Errors> errors)",
      "description": "Collects a stream of Errors into a map counting how many times each error appears."
    },
    {
      "name": "errorCounts(Collection<Errors> errors)",
      "description": "Iterates over a collection of Errors and builds a count map using updateErrorCounts."
    },
    {
      "name": "apiErrorCounts(Map<?, ApiError> errors)",
      "description": "Converts a map whose values are ApiError objects into an Errors‑count map."
    },
    {
      "name": "updateErrorCounts(Map<Errors,Integer> errorCounts, Errors error)",
      "description": "Increments the count for a given error in the supplied map (creates entry with count 1 if absent)."
    },
    {
      "name": "parseResponse(ByteBuffer buffer, RequestHeader requestHeader)",
      "description": "Static factory that parses a response from a buffer that contains both the response header and payload. It validates the correlation id and then delegates to the overloaded parseResponse(ApiKeys, …) method."
    },
    {
      "name": "parseResponse(ApiKeys apiKey, ByteBuffer responseBuffer, short version)",
      "description": "Huge switch‑statement that selects the concrete response class based on the ApiKeys value and calls its static parse method. Throws AssertionError for unknown keys."
    },
    {
      "name": "shouldClientThrottle(short version)",
      "description": "Indicates whether a client must apply throttling for this response version when the broker returns a non‑zero throttle time. Default implementation returns false; subclasses may override."
    },
    {
      "name": "apiKey()",
      "description": "Getter that returns the ApiKeys associated with this response."
    },
    {
      "name": "throttleTimeMs()",
      "description": "Abstract method that concrete responses implement to expose the throttle time (in ms) contained in the response schema, or 0 if the schema does not support throttling."
    },
    {
      "name": "maybeSetThrottleTimeMs(int throttleTimeMs)",
      "description": "Abstract mutator that sets the throttle time on the response when the underlying schema supports it; otherwise it is a no‑op."
    },
    {
      "name": "toString()",
      "description": "Overrides Object.toString() to return the string representation of the underlying protocol data object (data())."
    }
  ]
}
```

{
  "invocation_purpose": "The call invokes the static `parse` method of the `UpdateMetadataResponse` class to transform the raw `responseBuffer` (and the supplied `version` information) into a fully‑initialized `UpdateMetadataResponse` object. This parsing step interprets the binary protocol data received from the broker, applies version‑specific decoding logic, and returns a high‑level response instance that the rest of the client code can work with.",
  "cyclic_dependency_explanation": "If the `parse` method (or any helper it uses) internally triggers logic that eventually leads back to the code path which called `UpdateMetadataResponse.parse`, a cyclic dependency is formed. For example, `parse` might need to look up metadata about topics, which could invoke a request that again expects an `UpdateMetadataResponse` to be parsed, creating a loop where the parsing routine depends on the outcome of a process that itself requires the same parsing step. This mutual reliance between the parser and the caller constitutes a cyclic dependency in the system's control flow."
}

